1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger de  Blakinston was born about 1319, his father, Hugo de Blakiston, was 36 and his mother, Cecilia Fitz Ralph, was 29. He married Christina DE Washington about 1345, in Durham, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1349, at the age of 32."},"et":{"Abt 1319–about 1349":"umbes 1319–umbes 1349","1319–1349":"1319–1349","1321–Male":"1321–Surnud","1323–Female":"1323–Surnud","1345–1419":"1345–1419","1362–Male":"1362–Surnud","1285–1341":"1285–1341","1292–Female":"1292–Surnud","ABT 1345":"umbes 1345","1341":"1341","1285":"1285","1362":"1362","ABT 1315":"umbes 1315","Abt 1319":"umbes 1319","1292":"1292","1349":"1349","about 1349":"umbes 1349","1345":"1345","1323":"1323","1321":"1321","about 1345":"umbes 1345","1419":"1419","LIV. 1341":"1341","1319":"1319","Norton, Stockton-on-Tees district, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Norton, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blakiston, Durham, England":"Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1319–about 1349":"noin 1319–noin 1349","1319–1349":"1319–1349","1321–Male":"1321–Kuollut","1323–Female":"1323–Kuollut","1345–1419":"1345–